data.title: Top swimmers to compete in University of Michigan quad meet this weekend
data.meta_description: Michigan will be tested early this season when the Wolverines host three top-15 swim teams this weekend.
data.text:
Dylan Bosch, 200 Breaststroke

The University of Michigan men's swimming & diving team competes on the final day of the 2014 NCAA Championships on March 29, 2014, hosted by the University of Texas, in Austin, Texas.

(Courtesy photo | Michigan Athletics)

ANN ARBOR, MI - Some of the nation's top collegiate swimmers will race in Canham Natatorium this weekend in an early test for the University of Michigan.

The Wolverines will host Top-15 teams Texas, Indiana and Louisville on Friday and Saturday in a quad meet coach Mike Bottom considers one of the nation's fastest of the year.

"I don't think there will be a faster meet until we get into the conference championships in February and March," Bottom said. "We're seeing one of the best teams in the Big Ten, and the best team in the country in Texas. They almost won last year, they didn't lose anybody and they have the No. 1 recruiting class."

Michigan comes into the meet 1-0 after beating Iowa to open the season, but its three opponents each have identical records.

Facing top talent early has its benefits and helps the team keep focused on its goals, said senior captain Richard Funk

"It allows us to be as motivated as we would be at the end of the season, but in October, which is great for our fitness and shape going forward," Funk said. "Having this level of competition this early only helps us going into the later part of the season because we'll get fast and tough racing at the get-go."

Both the men's and women's teams will split their events starting at 6 p.m. Friday and 10 a.m. Saturday, with post-grad races showcasing some of the nation's top swimmers during breaks.

The meet will include four of the top eight American distance swimmers, including Michigan's Connor Jaeger and Sean Ryan, and Texas' Michael McBroom and Michael Klueh. Other notable post grads will include Emily Brunemann and Junya Koga of Club Wolverine, Louisville's Joao De Lucca and Indiana's Lindsay Vrooman.

Related: Michigan swim faces challenge of replacing 'one of the best senior classes in college swimming'

On the men's side, Michigan took fourth in last year's NCAA meet, with Texas finishing second, Indiana 10th and Louisville 11th. The Texas, Indiana and Louisville women's teams finished No. 9, 12 and 15, respectively.

U-M's men's team beat both Texas and Indiana last season, while the women's team fell to both. The Cardinals join the quad meet for the first time this year, making their dual-meet debut against the Wolverines.
